{
  "texts": [
    "Just as a comparison, the difference in average time between people who were on average rated 0 in effectiveness (90.75 seconds) and those who rated 6 in effectiveness (104.41) is lower than 15 seconds.",
    "Yet, increasing participants time by ~15-24 seconds did not seem to impact quality.",
    "One interpretation of these findings is that the association between time and quality is one such that higher quality reappraisers take more time, but the quality of their reappraisal is not driven by the time they take.",
    "Therefore, forcing people who are less good at reappraisal to spend more time reappraising should not improve their performance.",
    "Study 4: Does Knowledge of the Source of the Reappraisal Affect Quality?"
  ]
}